      <h1 class="hero-title">Where to Eat in Bermuda</h1>
      <p class="hero-subtitle">
        Bermuda's dining scene punches above its weight for an island of 64,000 people.
        Eating well here is entirely possible — it just requires knowing where to go
        and what you'll actually spend.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="container" style="padding-block: var(--space-12);">
    <div style="max-width: 800px; margin: 0 auto;">

      <!-- Intro / pricing context -->
      <div class="alert alert-info" style="margin-bottom: var(--space-8);">
        <strong>Pricing reality:</strong> Bermuda is genuinely expensive. A mid-range dinner
        for two with wine will run $100–140. Fine dining is $160–240 for two. A fish sandwich
        at a takeaway counter is $12–16. These are not tourist prices — they reflect the actual
        cost of importing almost everything. Budget accordingly and you won't be unpleasantly
        surprised.
      </div>

      <!-- Bermuda food you should know -->
      <section style="margin-bottom: var(--space-12);">
        <h2 style="margin-bottom: var(--space-6);">The food you need to know about</h2>

        <article style="margin-bottom: var(--space-8);">
          <span class="badge badge-tier-anchor" style="margin-bottom: var(--space-2);">Bermuda institution</span>
          <h3 style="margin: 0 0 var(--space-3);">The Bermuda fish sandwich</h3>
          <p>
            If you eat one thing in Bermuda, make it a fish sandwich. This is not a cautious tourist
            recommendation — it is what Bermudians eat. The classic version is a fried wahoo or
            rockfish fillet, tartar sauce, a slice of tomato, and coleslaw on a raisin bread roll
            (occasionally a white roll, but raisin is traditional). The bread is slightly sweet, the
            fish is fresh, and the whole construction is considerably better than the sum of its parts.
          </p>
          <p>
            <strong>Art Mel's Spicy Dicy</strong> in Hamilton is the most cited name — a small
            counter-service spot on North Street that has been making fish sandwiches for decades.
            Lunchtimes only; cash preferred; queue expected. Worth it. Other good options include
            Wahoo's Bistro in St. George's and various takeaway counters around the island.
            Do not eat your first fish sandwich at a hotel — the hotel version exists, but it is
            rarely the real thing.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article style="margin-bottom: var(--space-8);">
          <h3 style="margin: 0 0 var(--space-3);">Bermuda fish chowder</h3>
          <p>
            Bermuda fish chowder is the island's signature dish and is nothing like New England
            clam chowder. It is a deep-red, tomato-based stew with a complex, dark flavour that
            comes from long-cooked fish stock (traditionally rockfish or snapper), vegetables,
            and Bermudian black rum and sherry peppers sauce added at the table. Some versions
            have been simmering the base for days.
          </p>
          <p>
            The sherry peppers sauce — a Bermuda condiment made from small hot peppers infused
            in dry sherry — is essential. You'll find bottles of it on most restaurant tables.
            The rum finish is traditional and the dish is better with both. Most sit-down
            restaurants offer it as a starter; quality varies considerably between kitchens.
            The Hog Penny Pub version is a reliable benchmark.
          </p>
        </article>
      </section>

