      <!-- By vibe -->
      <section style="margin-bottom: var(--space-12);">
        <h2 style="margin-bottom: var(--space-6);">By vibe</h2>

        <article style="margin-bottom: var(--space-8);">
          <span class="badge badge-tier-anchor" style="margin-bottom: var(--space-2);">Splurge</span>
          <h3 style="margin: 0 0 var(--space-3);">Fine dining: Fourways Inn and Waterloo House</h3>
          <p>
            Fourways Inn in Paget is housed in a 17th-century manor and occupies a category of
            its own on the island — proper tablecloths, formal service, and a wine list that
            takes itself seriously. It is old Bermuda in a way that is either appealing or not,
            depending on your temperament. The food is competent European continental with local
            fish well represented. Budget $80–120 per person before wine.
          </p>
          <p>
            Waterloo House on Hamilton Harbour is the more contemporary of the two top-end
            options. The terrace over the water is one of the best tables on the island and
            the service is reliably the most polished in Hamilton. If you're going to spend
            serious money once, this is the room to do it in. Reserve well ahead for terrace
            seating in summer.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article style="margin-bottom: var(--space-8);">
          <span class="badge badge-tier-featured" style="margin-bottom: var(--space-2);">Mid-range</span>
          <h3 style="margin: 0 0 var(--space-3);">Hog Penny, Port O' Call, and Lemon Tree</h3>
          <p>
            The <strong>Hog Penny Pub</strong> on Burnaby Street in Hamilton is the island's most
            reliable mid-range restaurant — a British pub format with a proper kitchen, good
            Bermuda fish chowder, a decent burger, and a convivial atmosphere. It is a good place
            to eat alone. $40–55 per person with a drink.
          </p>
          <p>
            <strong>Port O' Call</strong>, also in Hamilton, is a step up in formality — seafood
            focused, with a stronger local fish selection than most Hamilton restaurants and a
            room that works for a business dinner or a slightly nicer evening out. $50–70 per person.
          </p>
          <p>
            <strong>Lemon Tree Cafe</strong> on Queen Street is the best daytime option in
            Hamilton — good sandwiches, fresh salads, reliable coffee, and a reasonable pace.
            Useful for a quick lunch between activities. $15–25 per person.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article style="margin-bottom: var(--space-8);">
          <span class="badge badge-tier-standard" style="margin-bottom: var(--space-2);">Casual / local</span>
          <h3 style="margin: 0 0 var(--space-3);">Art Mel's and the local chowder circuit</h3>
          <p>
            <strong>Art Mel's Spicy Dicy</strong> on North Street, Hamilton, is the fish sandwich
            institution. It is a small counter-service operation with no ambience and occasionally
            a long queue. Go anyway. It is one of the few genuinely local eating experiences that
            visitors can access without navigating private networks, and the food is excellent on
            its own terms.
          </p>
          <p>
            For fish chowder in a more casual register, the Swizzle Inn in Bailey's Bay
            (the famous rum swizzle pub) serves a solid bowl alongside the island's most
            atmospheric drinking room. Hog Penny remains the benchmark for the more refined
            version. Both are worth a visit; they are not interchangeable experiences.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article style="margin-bottom: var(--space-8);">
          <span class="badge badge-tier-standard" style="margin-bottom: var(--space-2);">Beach bar</span>
          <h3 style="margin: 0 0 var(--space-3);">Wahoo's Bistro, St. George's</h3>
          <p>
            Wahoo's Bistro sits on the harbour in St. George's and does exactly what a good
            beach bar should: cold drinks, a decent fish sandwich, some frozen cocktails, and a
            view of the water. It is tourist-friendly in the way that means it works for visitors
            without being an embarrassment. Combine with an afternoon at Tobacco Bay, which is
            a short taxi or scooter ride away.
          </p>
          <p>
            Mickey's Beach Bistro at Elbow Beach is the other obvious beach lunch option —
            right on the sand, with a longer menu than Wahoo's and a resort price premium that
            comes with the setting. Expect $50–70 per person for a lunch with drinks. The
            location is hard to argue with.
          </p>
        </article>
      </section>

      <!-- Practical notes -->
      <section style="background-color: var(--color-sand); border-radius: var(--radius-lg); padding: var(--space-8); margin-bottom: var(--space-10);">
        <h2 style="margin-bottom: var(--space-6);">Practical notes</h2>

        <h3 style="font-size: var(--text-xl); margin-bottom: var(--space-3);">Resort and hotel markup</h3>
        <p style="margin-bottom: var(--space-5);">
          Eating at your hotel or resort will cost significantly more than eating in Hamilton
          or at a standalone local restaurant. This is not a hidden surcharge — it reflects the
          genuine cost of operating a resort kitchen on a small island with high import costs.
          But if you eat every meal on-property, you are leaving most of Bermuda's dining scene
          on the table and spending more for the privilege. Even for one meal a day, making the
          effort to eat in town changes your trip noticeably.
        </p>

        <h3 style="font-size: var(--text-xl); margin-bottom: var(--space-3);">Reservations</h3>
        <p style="margin-bottom: var(--space-5);">
          Bermuda's restaurant sector is small. Popular places — particularly in Hamilton — fill
          up earlier than visitors expect. For any mid-range or above restaurant on a Friday or
          Saturday night between May and September, book at least three to five days ahead. For
          Fourways or Waterloo House at the weekend, book further ahead than that.
        </p>
        <p style="margin-bottom: var(--space-4);">
          OpenTable covers about 88 Bermuda restaurants and is the easiest way to check
          availability and book online. The local alternative is Table.bm, which lists some
          properties not on OpenTable.
        </p>

        <div style="display: flex; flex-wrap: wrap; gap: var(--space-4);">
          <div>
            <a href="/Pilot.BM/go/opentable-bermuda" rel="nofollow sponsored" class="btn btn-primary">
              Check Availability on OpenTable →
            </a>
            <p style="font-size: var(--text-xs); color: var(--color-muted); margin-top: var(--space-1);">
              [PLACEHOLDER affiliate link — real ID to be set in affiliate-links.ts after approval]
            </p>
